When I moved to Harare in 1985, social justice issues were at the core of Zimbabwe's national health policy.
After the new government broke free from the long independence war, it immediately announced a socialist policy: making healthcare services and primary education basic free services.
The large-scale rural health service centers make it possible for 80% of the population to reach within a two-hour walk, which is truly remarkable progress.
In the year of Zimbabwe's independence in 1980, 25% of children received routine immunizations.
By 1990, just ten years later, this proportion had risen to 80%.
I am very honored to be able to participate in this transformation, in this revolution.
The excitement and comradery are both very genuine.
Working shoulder to shoulder with the outstanding people of Zimbabwe, scientists, doctors, and activists, I feel that I am not only participating in an African independence movement, but also a global public health movement for progress.
I have also faced some daunting difficulties.
In 1985, the year I arrived, Zimbabwe reported its first case of AIDS.
In the early 1980s, I cared for several AIDS patients when I was training at Harlem Hospital, but... we never imagined what we would encounter in Africa.
When I first arrived there, the infection rate was about 2%.
This proportion rapidly increased, and by the time I left Harare 17 years later, one in every four adults was infected.
By the mid-1990s, I had informed hundreds of vibrant young people that their AIDS virus tests were positive.
I witnessed colleagues and friends die, as well as my students and hospital patients.
Faced with this situation, my colleagues and I opened a clinic.
We demonstrated how to use condoms.
We conduct education and promotion at schools and workplaces.
We conduct research and provide advice on how to protect themselves for partners of AIDS-infected individuals.
We are working very hard on all of this. I believe I had already done my best at that time.
I provided the best treatment measures, at least under the conditions at that time.
But I did not make constructive changes.
Former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan once openly admitted that it was his personal mistake that led to the genocide in Rwanda.
In 1994, he was the leader of the UN peacekeeping department.
At the tenth anniversary commemoration of the genocide, he recalled that at the time, he believed he had done everything he could, but it was only after the genocide that he realized there was much more he could and should do to sound the alarm and seek support.
The outbreak of AIDS caught the medical community off guard. The World Health Organization estimates that thirty-nine million people have died from this disease today. Many, like myself, feel regret and sorrow for not being able to stop it earlier.
But when I was living in Zimbabwe, I did not realize that I was an advocate or a politician.
I thought it was because of my medical knowledge that I went there, because of my clinical and infectious disease research.
I have always felt that my job is to take care of patients and to better understand the characteristics of the infected population through research. I hope to slow down the spread of the virus.
I realized that the proportion of marginalized groups in society infected with and dying from AIDS is surprisingly high.
In the sugar cane plantations, which resemble feudal estates more than modern enterprises, 60% of pregnant women tested positive for the AIDS virus.
My job is to show people that being infected is not a moral decline, but is related to patriarchy, forced labor, and colonialism.
Most white people are safe and sound.
As medical experts, our methods are unfortunately powerless: we beg people to change their personal behaviors, use condoms, and reduce the number of partners.
The infection rate continues to climb. As our most effective weapon against the virus, treatment is unaffordable for the entire public sector in Africa when it has already become feasible in the West.
I did not boldly state that the unequal access to life-saving drugs or the potential issues within the economic and political systems are the driving forces behind the high infection rates among such a large population.
I made excuses for my silence, reminding myself that I am just a visitor in this country. Ringing the alarm bell may lead to being expelled, making it impossible for me to do my job, take care of my patients, and conduct urgently needed research.
So I did not boldly speak out against the government's early AIDS policies.
I did not express my concerns loudly enough.
Many doctors and healthcare workers may feel that I did nothing wrong.
Our commitment to patients, like the Hippocratic Oath and its various versions, is a sacred and inviolable doctor-patient relationship.
I do everything in my power for each of my patients.
But I know that the infectious diseases that arise with the division in our society reflect not only biological phenomena, but more importantly, the phenomena of marginalization, intolerance, racial discrimination, gender discrimination, and class discrimination.
