Medical anthropologists, such as Paul Farmer, working on AIDS in Haiti, refer to it as structural violence: structural because inequality is rooted in the political and economic organization of our society, often ignored by the privileged and ruling classes; violence because its effects, such as premature death, suffering, and disease, are violent.
We do very little for patients if we do not realize these social injustices.
Ringing the alarm bell is the first step in guiding public health in the right direction, this is the way we seek support, to break through together, to create a way for real change.
So now, I have not remained silent.
I speak boldly about many things, even if it makes the listener uncomfortable, even if it makes me uncomfortable.
Many of these are about racial segregation and organized racism, things that should not happen in this country, things that should not exist in medical practice or public health.
But they do exist, and we pay the price of shortened lives for it.
This is the reason why the impact of racism on healthcare in the United States continues to sound the alarm. The ongoing, organized violence against people of color is closely related to our tragic history of 250 years of slavery, 90 years of racial discrimination, and 60 years of imperfect equality. It is for this reason that as the Commissioner of Health in New York City, this is the focus of my work.
In New York City, the premature mortality rate, defined as death before the age of 65, is 50% higher for Black people compared to White people.
In 2012, black women faced more than 10 times the risk of pregnancy-related deaths compared to white women.
Despite the significant progress we have made in reducing infant mortality rates, the mortality rate of Black infants in the first year after birth is still nearly three times that of White infants.
New York City is not an exception.
These statistical data are similar across the entire United States.
A recent analysis by The New York Times reported that there are approximately 15 million missing black men nationwide.
The author points out that among every six black men aged 25 to 54, at least one disappears from daily life due to incarceration or premature death.
Young black people face disproportionate acts of violence in their daily lives, which is very unfair and is present in recent protests where the slogan "Black Lives Matter" has been prominently raised.
But we need to remember that in the current situation and outcomes of ordinary healthcare, as well as the persistent and disproportionately high disease rates of heart disease, cancer, diabetes, AIDS, those diseases that slowly and quietly devour life, are causing more Black lives to prematurely vanish.
As the "Black Lives Matter" movement unfolds, I feel frustrated and angry. Medical groups are hesitant even in their research and work, and even in the use of the term "racism."
Every time I mention it, you probably already have a sense of it.
Medical students, dressed in white coats, protested against biological weapons with their lives, but medical groups largely stand by in the face of persistent racial discrimination and its significant impact on disease conditions and mortality rates.
I am very concerned that the trend towards personalized and targeted drugs, searching for biological and genetic targets to better design therapies, may inadvertently lead us to lose sight of the bigger picture. This is exactly the scenario of daily life, where an individual's life, growth, work, and place of love significantly impact the health of the community. For many of us, poor health is a reality.
In our daily lives, as healthcare workers, whether in clinics or conducting research, we are witnesses to great injustices: the homeless, unable to follow medical advice because they must prioritize more pressing matters; young transgender individuals planning suicide because our society is too harsh; single mothers feeling compelled to take responsibility for their children's poor health.
As healthcare workers, our role is not only to treat our patients but also to sound the alarm and advocate for change.
Regardless of whether it is reasonable or not, our social position makes our voice more credible, and we should not waste it.
I regret not being candid in Zimbabwe. I have made a commitment to myself that as the Commissioner of Health in New York City, I will use every opportunity to sound the alarm and seek support for healthcare equality.
I will speak out against racial discrimination, and I hope you can join me, and I will also join you when you speak out against gender discrimination or any form of inequality.
It's time for us to rise up and boldly speak out against structural inequalities together.
We do not need to have all the answers to advocate for change.
We just need courage.
The health of our patients, our own health, all depend on this.
